      <hedline>
        <hl1>Just How Safe Is 'Wireless' Pollution?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sylvia Keller letter on Paul L Sterne's July 30 letter says cell phone towers are not improvement over telephone poles and may be harmful to health (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the letter ''Wireless Master Plan Urged for Westchester'' from Paul L. Sterne of Dobbs Ferry [July 30]:</p>
        <p>Mr. Sterne is lucky that his brain can still filter out what he calls the ''visual pollution'' of telephone wires.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Regarding the letter ''Wireless Master Plan Urged for Westchester'' from Paul L. Sterne of Dobbs Ferry [July 30]:</p>
        <p>Mr. Sterne is lucky that his brain can still filter out what he calls the ''visual pollution'' of telephone wires.</p>
        <p>If he thinks that cell phone towers are an ''improvement'' and that a wireless master plan is the environmental and aesthetic answer to all our problems -- just wait!</p>
        <p>Wait until you get sick. There is a hidden epidemic of people who are suffering severe and acute health effects from exposure to cellular towers and cell phones. What about the radiation that is being emitted 24 hours a day, enveloping us all? Do you think it is safe? We shall see . . .</p>
        <p>SYLVIA KELLER  Brooklyn</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
